<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="HEP01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">John</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Hepburn</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> St Clair, 309, identifies Hepburn as an Scottish landowner whom Godwin hoped might 
    offer security for a loan (see also the very extensive correspondence with John Fairley in Scotland where 
    Godwin discusses the details of the proposals).  Godwin had first met him at 
    Horne Tooke's, and Hepburn clearly had an interest in radical politics. Despite the failure to secure 
    Godwin's loans, they remained in touch. Hepburn was in Scotland when Godwin visited in 1816 and 
    they met several times, and Hepburn seems to have been in London for a visit in 1818 and 1822, in 
